div.p:
Mr. DITTEMORE moved that the minority report be laid on the table.
                                   The yeas and nays were called, and the vote resulted--yeas, 20;
                                   nays, 16.

Mr. OFFUTT demanded the yeas and nays, which resulted--yeas, 32;
                                   nays, 67. So that motion being rejected, the question recurred
                                   upon Mr. Heller's to reconsider the per diem bill.

Mr. Speaker EDWARDS (Mr. Offutt in the chair) joined the gentleman
                                   from Parke (Mr. Woodard) in his objection to the proposed change;
                                   to make it would be only to send the bill back to the Senate.

The bill was read the second time, the constitutional rule
                                   suspended, and the bill read the third time and passed--yeas, 31;
                                   nays, 8.

